Bolaji Akinduro, executive chairman of Total Grace Oil and Gas Investment Limited, has sued the Economic and Financial Commission (EFCC) for Illegally declaring him wanted.

In the suit filed on Wednesday before a federal high court in Lagos, Akinduro submitted that the EFCC declared him wanted illegally without any form of judicial intervention, recourse to constitutional safeguards, or order of a court.

The businessman is seeking a court order for the EFCC to remove his name from the wanted list published on the commission‚Äôs official website or any other platform, including X, formerly Twitter.

Akinduro is seeking N5 billion as ‚Äúgeneral damages‚Äù.

Parallelfacts earlier reported on Saturday, the EFCC declared Akinduro wanted for allegedly obtaining money under false pretence and committed ‚Äústealing by conversion‚Äù.

On Thursday, the Supreme Court declared all Bangladeshi migrants who entered Assam on or after March 25, 1971, as illegal migrants. 

Citing the significant negative impact on the state's culture and demographics, the Court urged the Union and state governments to expedite the identification, detection, and deportation of these migrants. 

A five-judge bench delivered the verdict with a four-to-one majority, upholding the validity of Section 6A of the Citizenship Act, introduced in December 1985 in accordance with the Assam Accord signed by the Rajiv Gandhi government with student unions protesting against the influx of Bangladeshi migrants.

[Supreme Court, Assam, Illegal Immigrants]

Pune: Father-Son Duo Cheated Man of Rs 5 Lakh With Fake Job Promise in IT Department

Dehu Road, 18th October 2024: A man was duped for nearly Rs 5 lakh by a father-son duo who promised him a job in the Income Tax Department of the Government of India. The complainant, a defence contractor, approached the accused duo because he was seeking employment in the Income Tax Department. The fraud occurred between December 2022 and March 2024 in the Dehu Road area.

Gaurav Harish Bhatia (aged 43, a resident of Dehu Road) filed a complaint at Dehu Road Police Station. A case has been registered against Praveen Eknath Panchal (aged 22) and Eknath Panchal (aged 50), both residents of Kalewadi.

The charges include IPC Sections 420 (cheating and dishonestly inducing delivery of property), 468 (forgery for the purpose of cheating), 471 (using a forged document as genuine), and 34 (acts done by several persons in furtherance of common intention).

According to police reports, Gaurav was lured by the father-son duo with the promise of a job in the IT Department. The accused cheated him by providing a fake appointment letter and collecting Rs 4,78,700 from him, both in cash and through online transactions over time.
